---
folder: services
id-format: "NNNN-kebab-slug.md"
---
## Purpose
One doc per deployed workload on the cluster (an app, MCP server, or infra service like
the croc relay). Captures what it is, why it exists, how it's exposed, and its
operational shape. NOT the general cluster design (→ architectures/) and NOT the story of
a specific outage (→ incidents/). The authoritative manifest always lives at
`clusters/homelab/apps/<name>.yaml`; this doc distills it and adds the "why".

## File template
Frontmatter: `id`, `title`, `status`, `created`, `updated`, `links`.
Body:
- `## Summary` — one paragraph: what the service does and who uses it.
- `## Deployment` — namespace, image, key resources (memory/cpu/storage), manifest path.
- `## Exposure` — how it's reached: Cloudflare tunnel host, Tailscale (operator vs Ingress)
  hostname, or ClusterIP-only. Note LAN exposure if any.
- `## Operational notes` — startup quirks, probes, scaling limits, secrets handling.
- `## Related` — links.

## Retro rules
Extract services deployed, migrated, or materially reconfigured. New workload agreed and
applied → create. Config changed with lasting effect (memory bump, exposure change, image
pin) → update the doc in place, bump `updated`. Ignore transient live patches that Flux
reverts (record the durable, committed state). Note when a service exists in-cluster but
NOT in git (drift) under `## Operational notes`.

## Cross-linking
Links to `[[architectures/NNNN]]` (exposure/hosting decisions), `[[incidents/NNNN]]`
(outages that hit this service), and `[[runbooks/NNNN]]` (how to deploy/operate it).
